{
  "text": "The potential pathogenic mechanisms mentioned in the preceding text help explain the phenotypes we and others [CITATION_1] have observed in RPE65 D477G KI mice. These mice exhibit an overall visual cycle insufficiency manifested by ERG suppression in older mice, a delay in visual chromophore regeneration and the accumulation of retinyl esters in both heterozygous and homozygous mice. These phenotypes can be attributed to reduced levels of functional RPE65 in KI mice, likely due to a reduction in RPE65 protein levels resulting from its ubiquination and proteolytic degradation (Fig. 12 ) as well as a potential dominant-negative effect exerted by the D477G mutant on visual chromophore production which could suppress visual cycle activity to a pathogenic level [CITATION_2] . Given that RPE65 is likely a dimeric protein in vivo (32), the dominant-negative effect could be explained by heterodimer formation between WT and D477G resulting in potential mislocalization and/or degradation of the dimeric complex, thus reducing WT protein function (Fig. 12) . Besides effects on visual cycle function, we also observed pathological autofluorescent bodies in the retinas of heterozygous and homozygous KI mice by SLO imaging. Although these structures cannot be definitively identified by SLO, prior studies on animal disease models including Palm \u00c0/\u00c0 (20), E150K opsin [CITATION_3] and ABCA4",
